cusing on the emergence of private and state corporations in Yunnan Province during the late 1800s and early 1900s, the book reveals how entrepreneurs centralized corporate power even as they expanded their businesses throughout the Southwest and into Tibet, Southeast Asia, and eastern China. Bringing wealth and cosmopolitan lifestyles to their hometowns, the merchant-owners also gained greater access to commodities at the expense of the Southwest's many indigenous minority communities. Meanwhile, new concepts of development shaped the creation of state-run corporations, which further concentrated resources in the hands of outsiders. The book reveals how important new ideas and structures of power, now central to the Communist Party's repertoire of rule and oppression, were forged, not along China's east coast, but along the nation's internal borderlands. It is a must-read for anyone wishing to learn about China's unique state capitalism and its contribution to inequality.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aCorporationszChina, SouthwestxHistory. 0aMinoritieszChina, SouthwestxEconomic conditionsy19th century. 0aMinoritieszChina, SouthwestxEconomic conditionsy20th century. 7aHISTORY / Asia / General.2bisacsh  aChina.  aSoutheast Asia.  aYunnan.  aborderlands.  acorporations.  aethnicity.  ainequality.  anew accounting history.  astate-building.  astate-owned enterprises.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020 Englishz978311070471608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2020z9783110704518oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020 Englishz978311070473008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE History 2020z9783110704525oZDB-23-DEG08iTitle is part of 